Acute pancreatitis complicated by pancreatic ascites. Diagnostic and therapeutic difficulties. The authors report a case of acute pancreatitis, complicated by pancreatic-peritoneal fistula and ascites in 26 year old man, with a history of excessive alcoholic intake. Biochemical investigation of ascitic and pleural fluids, which revealed markedly elevated activity of pancreatic enzymes and protein indicated their pancreatic origin. After 25 days of treatment with somatostatin and parenteral nutrition, the condition of the patient improved and he was dismissed home.